<blockquote>   <p>MySQL: <code>REFERENCES</code> vs <code>FOREIGN KEY</code> + <code>REFERENCES</code></p> </blockquote>  <p>I thought that <code>REFERENCES</code>was some sort of shorthand syntax for the more verbose <code>FOREIGN KEY REFERENCES</code> syntax.</p>  <p>However, the below table is not acting like it is constrained by a foreign key constraint. I can easily add a tuple with a <code>courseid</code> not in the <code>Courses</code> relation.</p>  <p>Can someone clarify this issue?</p>  <pre><code>CREATE TABLE `Exam`(     `courseid` VARCHAR(20) REFERENCES `Courses`(courseid) ON DELETE RESTRICT ON UPDATE CASCADE,     `examno` INT(1) DEFAULT 1 CHECK(`examno` &gt;= 1),     `weight` FLOAT(5) DEFAULT 1 CHECK(`weight` &gt; 0),     PRIMARY KEY(courseId, examNo) ); </code></pre>